I will post the whole story tomorrow but I am sitting in an emergency room with this little guy after what has already been a rough week. He is critical!!
Leg was ripped off by being accidentally run over at a golf course so we trapped him and @goodkarmapetrescue is taking he and his brother (trapped them both at the same time) into the rescue and all of the expenses to go with it.

He will most likely need to have emergency surgery by a specialist tonight and that alone will come with a few thousand $$$ vet bill to @goodkarmapetrescue . They have had so many cases like this they've bravely taken on and have taken a turn for the worse that they are in major debt.

Exactly a week ago right around this exact time we lost our beautiful tuxedo Mojo suddenly and completely unexpectedly.
This post is to share a very important article we came across to spread awareness of the importance of knowing your cat's behavior and not hesitating to get them to a vet and yearly checkup.
Having dealt directly with 2 of the 5 common cat illnesses in the article (link below) within a 13 month period, I cannot stress this enough. It wouldn't have changed anything in Mojo's case by the time he displayed symptoms but catching Venus acting strange and getting her emergency treatment saved her life. She too went from seeming fine in the morning to suddenly limp & lethargic laying in one of the litter boxes. She overcame a UTI & complete urinary blockage (which took a while to completely heal from & rarely happens in females) which is one of the illnesses mentioned and Mojo as you know crossed the rainbow bridge due to one of the other conditions mentioned which is HCM (cardiomyopathy). Please take a moment & become familiar with the symptoms of these silent killers. The more aware you are, the better chance your pet will have of not having to face critical condition or death.
Here is the link to the site.
https://www.petfinder.com/cats/cat-health/serious-cat-illnesses-vet-diagnose/
I know those on Instagram can't click it so I'll be putting it in the bio section. The pain I had to watch 2 of my 3 cats go through is something I hope I can save you and your pets from by sharing knowledge like this. Thanks again for all of the kind words on Mojo's posts last week. It meant a lot to us. Xoxo Venus's big humans & 3 little humans 😽😘

To clean or not to clean....that is the question. Open discussion. I want to especially hear from veterinarians and vet techs.
Mama was told at a visit in December that I should get a cleaning which requires being put under anesthesia which has risks of its own. That makes her very nervous. After this pic was taken we went for another vet visit and one of the techs just scraped off the tarter/plaque visible in this pic with her nail.
All pet parents are nervous about their fur baby having to be put under so my question is.... I'm 8 years old, my chompers look and work well (just ask my little human's toys he leave around and I hunt as trophies for mama...nerf darts are a favorite) so how necessary is it to have this tooth cleaning procedure? Is it possible to do it with less risk than being put under just like a surgical procedure? Halo had hers done when her first eye had to come out from Glaucoma otherwise she would've had the same question for her. Are there safer ways to protect against decay or what could turn into a bad tooth or worse? Or it up there on the importance list to where the benefits of having the cleaning far outweigh the risks of general anesthesia? What do stray cats do who live outdoors for 20 years? Mama had a neighbor in FL who has 5 indoor/outdoor kitties that she took in in 1995 as kittens/strays and they're all alive and well with never having to go to a vet. She feeds cheap store bought food, use cheap litter (or outdoors), and they're 22 years old.
Anyway, what are your thoughts and experiences on feline tooth cleaning and the risks associated?
Thanks in advance for your input! 😽😽

As requested, a video of Roo. He doesn't put weight on his right front leg (so he's a tripod) when he walks but he can use it to play and pull his claws on a scratch post.
A little background on Roo:
He was not bred this way. He was rescued by someone who witnessed someone else throwing him away like trash into a lake in a plastic bag likely because he was not normal like the rest of the litter. Luckily this other person saw this happen & brought him to @florida_humane_society where they adopted him out as a kitten.
Three years later he was returned by those adopters in very bad shape, emaciated. He was missing patches of fur and we recently noticed (if you compare to the pic posted Thursday) that his "pouch" has fur on it now. When we got him we didn't think there ever was fur there.
He sat at Florida Humane Society for 6 months until we went there met him, and fell in love with all of the reasons that one person literally threw him away (probably the deformed kitten of a litter) and another neglected him and ultimately returned him like a bad product. Where they saw deformities and some neurological challenges we saw uniqueness, a sweet personality that was dying to be loved, and a cat that deserved a chance. He was very skittish when we first got him (almost a year ago) but he looks so much different and has gone from a scared boy that would hide all day and jump & scatter every time you walked by him to a very affectionate trusting and friendly boy who jumps at every chance to occupy lap space. He is so content and happy and his purrs are a daily reminder of how one man's trash can be another's treasure.
He has radial hypoplasia which is why his front legs are bent, abnormally large rear legs to compensate so he can stand up steady, crossed eyes, big ears, a big crooked tail that was most likely broken after birth, and we LOVE all of those things about him!
We fell in love with all the reasons someone else thought he was trash and he didn't deserve to live.

Microchips, TNR, Collars!
Know what makes me sad? Kitties who sneak out or run away.... but worse, when they don't have a microchip, collar, and are not spayed/neutered. Mama stopped today to pick up a kitty who had been hit by a car in front of a school campus w/ an elementary, middle, and high school. He was already deceased and had likely been hit last night. She's done this before for a few reasons. It's hurtful/sad for kids to see animals lying roadside (esp in front of a school) and she takes them to a nearby vet who will scan for a microchip in hopes she can bring someone closure if the kitty has a human. If no human comes forward (yes she searches everywhere for missing cat notices) the kitty will at least be cremated and not just left on the road to disintegrate.
This kitty had no collar, wasn't neutered, and didn't have a microchip. He was likely a stray but there are so many stories of lost and found pets with no identification and mama wants to drive in the importance of wearing a safety breakaway collar with an ID tag and microchipping your pet so you can be reunited. Equally, if not more important is spaying and neutering. This poor kitty was probably part of a stray colony, a colony that will grow larger and larger if our humans don't help. There are TNR (trap, neuter, return) programs just about everywhere. Please consider volunteering some time to this very important cause to keep more and more strays from being born homeless.
The recent hurricanes bring to light another reason why microchipping is so helpful even if your pet never goes outside. We never know how natural disasters or other unforeseen events may affect us where we furbabies might wander away from home. We want to be reunited with our humans so please make sure we have a way to get back to you if we get lost.
Our thoughts and purrayers are with those affected by the recent storms and other tragic events happening in various places. 🙏😽
Thanks for listening! XOXO

Halo is at the emergency vet with her 2nd battle with glaucoma. Back in September she had to have her right eye removed and the biopsy revealed it was primary glaucoma meaning it's hereditary & that inevitably we'd be right here dealing with the other eye. 😿
She's going to be sedated and the eye fully examined to determine the best course of action for this eye. From what we can tell (which has progressed so quickly in a matter of days just like last time), the vision is now gone during the day too (it was just a night a couple weeks ago) and she'll likely have to have this eye removed as well. She wasn't in pain until today and last week I proactively made an appt with the eye specialist because I knew we were getting close & needed to create a plan of action for when things got bad (which is when vision is totally lost). The appt was for 4:30 today. We didn't make it because of her waking up panting with pain and no vision at all. We brought her to emergency so she didn't have to suffer all day. This is how fast this awful disease progresses. Unlike people, pets can go from doing ok and managing with pressure drops to ending up at emergency within a weekend!
Please read up on glaucoma and become familiar with the signs/symptoms. Many mistake a wet eye for seasonal allergies and it could be glaucoma. Cats can get glaucoma too so this isn't just for dog owners. Better to check and be safe than sorry.
So now we wait.... we will update as soon as we know more.
XOXO
UPDATE: pressures were in the 80's & there is no vision so enucleation (eye removal) will be performed just like 9 months ago. Unfortunately that's just the way glaucoma ends most times. She will be pain free and back home tonight. This ordeal will finally be over and she can start acclimating to getting around without vision. Thank you all for all the love and well wishes! 😘😽

I was asked to share a special & personal adoption story in light of the 25 million pets adopted through @petfinder. I couldn't think of a story more special and inspiring than Roo's. @roothekangaroocat 😺 .
Roo was born with genetic abnormalities & was rescued by someone who witnessed him cruelly being thrown into a lake. He was adopted out shortly after, still a kitten.
Three years later he was returned emaciated. He was missing patches of fur, skittish, & in an adoption room surrounded by gorgeous cats.
He sat at the shelter, skipped over for 6 months until we met him, and fell in love with all of the reasons that one person literally threw him away & another neglected him, returning him like a defective product. Where they saw deformities & some neurological challenges we saw uniqueness, a sweet personality that was dying to be loved, & a cat that deserved a chance.
He has a condition called radial hypoplasia which is why his front legs are bent, & has abnormally large rear legs so he can stand up steady. He has crossed eyes, big ears, & a crooked tail but we ❤️ all of those things about him! We chose him for the very reasons others looked away.
He was very skittish when we first got him but he looks so much different & has gone from a scared boy to a very affectionate trusting/friendly boy who jumps at every chance to occupy lap space. His purrs are so self rewarding & a daily reminder of how one man's trash can be another's treasure.

Kitty Heaven has gained a new angel. 😿👼
Many of you grew to know & love Mojo through our posts so we wanted to share with you that very unexpectedly Mojo was taken from us just after midnight this morning. Mojo & Venus both were rescued by us the same year just months apart in 2009. He was around a year old and she was just a couple months old. They grew fond of each other quickly & have always been close.
What we can tell you factually as we don't have the technical terms yet is that last night we noticed he had a deep but short/labored breathing pattern. We took him to the emergency clinic immediately. His O2 saturation was 71 & he started to breath with an open mouth. He was put in an oxygen chamber where he was stabilized enough to get an X-Ray. His insides were full of fluid, had an enlarged heart, fluid around the heart itself also & the prognosis was that his condition (heart related) was beyond being able to save him. When he was brought to us so we could hold him as he was humanely put to rest he had only been out of the oxygen chamber for a few moments & he started gasping & started to die right there so the solution was injected into his IV immediately so he could go in peace surrounded by love. It was a much quicker goodbye than we had hoped for but that is how quickly this condition went from "something isn't right" to lethal. I've said it before & I want to reiterate. Please, if you notice anything change about your cat's behavior DO NOT WAIT...get them to a vet ASAP! In our case we did catch it early & took immediate action but it wouldn't have made a difference in his case as his condition was inoperable. If we hadn't taken him when we did he would've died overnight alone while we slept. However, often times you CAN catch treatable conditions if you seek medical attention quickly. I wish his was treatable because we would've done whatever was necessary to save him. It was so hard to say goodbye!
Mojo we love & miss you so much! We hope that sharing your story will help someone else's pet get early detection as more people become aware of how important it is to watch for behavior changes and act quickly. You will live 4ever in our hearts!

This is a pic from 2013, a day I'll never forget. On this day, 9/21/13 we almost lost Venus from something totally preventable and we want to share her story with you in the hopes that it will spread awareness and save lives. When this post was shared in 2013 that's exactly what happened. We got a lot of comments and inbox messages that due to having read the info in the post about Venus's story, people were able to recognize the signs that something was wrong with their pet & in turn save their pet's life. It's too long to post here so I've put the link to her FB page in the bio. All posts are public so I don't think you need to have a Fb account to be able to read the posts. Please read and share this info. This isn't about likes or shares, it's about awareness and saving lives and it works! This day brings back one of the scariest & saddest days of my life not knowing for the first 48 hours if she would pull through but also makes me so very grateful that she was able to be saved and is still here with us today. Thanks everyone! XOXO 😽😽😽*****added info:
A lot of people who didn't go to or can't go to Facebook are asking what happened and I guess I left that out. The story is detailed in Facebook but the short short version is she suffered a complete urinary blockage which is almost unheard of in females. Both males and females get urinary tract infections but usually only males get blocked. She had to be this way for 4 days with a catheter and IV with weeks of extra meds and complications but made a full recovery. Thanks for asking and thanks to all who have shared your stories, advice, kind words, etc. What you shared may save someone's pet's life. 😊😽

Many of you have been asking for a Halo update so here you go:
Halo is doing great and is back to her usual high energy Shiba Inu self. She was actually back to herself two days following the surgery. She has adjusted to having only one eye so well and her fur will soon grow in the rest of the way. This pic was just taken today.
For those who don't know the story, Halo had a watery and squinty eye one morning and was taken to the vet the same day. That vet diagnosed her with conjunctivitis and we followed his treatment plan. After a week of not seeing significant improvement and Halo seeming to be in more pain, I took her for a 2nd opinion. She was diagnosed with glaucoma which progressed extremely quickly to the point of it now being an emergency. We then went to the emergency vet who confirmed the diagnosis. The eye was tested for vision and there was no response. Glaucoma had already blinded that eye and she was clearly in much more pain than even the day before. There was no saving the eye so we followed the ophthalmologists advice to remove the eye and relieve Halo of her pain. Surgery was done just hours later and it was so nice seeing her relaxed and not in pain anymore.
She has recovered so nicely but we have to give her drops daily and watch the other eye because the biopsy came back that it was primary glaucoma. Shiba Inus are genetically predisposed to this and most often by the time you notice symptoms it's already BAD. If you have a dog please read up on glaucoma and what to watch for. I hope by sharing Halo's story it will save someone else's dog from going through this. Also, veterinarians, please please please do a pressure test when dogs present eye problems. She may have still lost the eye if the 1st vet caught it but we could've saved her a week of pain, suffering, and aggravation with us putting drops in her eyes 2x per day treating the wrong thing. You Shiba owners know exactly what I'm talking about.
Thank you all so much for your thoughts and support. 😽😽

Roo before/after - 14 months after adopting...
A little background on Roo:
He was not bred this way. He was rescued by someone who witnessed someone else throwing him away like trash into a lake in a plastic bag likely because he was not normal like the rest of the litter. Luckily this other person saw this happen & brought him to @florida_humane_society where they adopted him out as a kitten.
Three years later he was returned by those adopters in very bad shape, emaciated. He was missing patches of fur and we recently noticed (if you compare to recent pics) that his "pouch" has fur on it now & all of his fur is more shiny & fluffy . When we got him we didn't think there ever was fur there.
He sat at Florida Humane Society for 6 months until we went there met him, and fell in love with all of the reasons that one person literally threw him away (probably the deformed kitten of a litter) and another neglected him and ultimately returned him like a bad product. Where they saw deformities and some neurological challenges we saw uniqueness, a sweet personality that was dying to be loved, and a cat that deserved a chance. He was very skittish when we first got him (almost a year ago) but he looks so much different and has gone from a scared boy that would hide all day and jump & scatter every time you walked by him to a very affectionate trusting and friendly boy who jumps at every chance to occupy lap space. He is so content and happy and his purrs are a daily reminder of how one man's trash can be another's treasure.
He has radial hypoplasia which is why his front legs are bent, abnormally large rear legs to compensate so he can stand up steady, crossed eyes, big ears, a big crooked tail that was most likely broken after birth, and we LOVE all of those things about him!
We fell in love with all the reasons someone else thought he was trash and that he didn't deserve to live.

Halo is home resting & Venus wasted no time stepping in to comfort & protect her. It's amazing how they know when something is wrong.
If you missed the last post, Halo had her 2nd eye removed today due to primary glaucoma leading to an extreme overnight change in pressures we've been managing with drops. All of the sudden it went from the drops being a life changer to the glaucoma progressing in hyper speed overnight spiking pressure & causing pain. The last post gives more details & like always, I want to use our unfortunate incident to spread awareness about this nasty disease. Please please please google glaucoma in cats/dogs & become familiar with the symptoms which are extremely subtle & hard to notice in early stages. Often times by the time you notice something it's too late. It's different from humans & the way we can manage it & keep it at bay for years.
I want to give a big thank you to Animal Emergency Center Rochester & staff for taking such good care of her again as an emergency when the eye specialist couldn't fit her in & also for being so patient & understanding, taking extra time to explain everything. It's over now & she can just put it behind her & recover.
Another big thank you to all of you for sending love, positive vibes, prayers, & for sharing your own stories of this same scenario happening to you and how your blind dog is thriving. We needed that encouragement because we feel so bad for her. 😢😿
You guys are the best & made this a whole lot easier to deal with today with all the love. 😘😽
We are prepared to give her the extra attention she'll need while adjusting to being blind & navigating around the house.
Again, please familiarize yourself with glaucoma especially if you have a breed who is known for being genetically predisposed. Shiba Inus aren't on those lists but just about everyone we've been to says they see it in Shibas all the time so even if your dog isn't on the list know the signs anyway. Don't dismiss a watery eye for seasonal allergies. It could be as simple as that or the start of glaucoma. Better to check pressures and catch it early if it is the onset of glaucoma.
Thanks again everyone!

Today is National Cat Day. 😺 .
It's also a bitter sweet day because exactly 2 years ago today our beloved Mojo was taken from us suddenly due to cardiomyopathy. He was only 6. 😿❤️.
In his memory and in honor of National Cat Day, we'd like to emphasize the importance of taking action the minute you notice odd behavior from your pets. They are so tough and good at hiding pain, by the time they show symptoms it's often too late with some of these diseases and illnesses. This was the case with Mojo. Playing that morning, labored breathing that night with an enlarged heart and fluid throughout his chest. He peacefully crossed the rainbow bridge but left a hole in our hearts as we really didn't think we wouldn't be bringing him home that night. 😿 🌈.
We almost lost Venus in 2013 from a urinary tract infection turned full blockage, (blockage almost unheard of in females). The only "off" thing we noticed was one of the 3 cats was peeing in random places but we thought it was behavioral because of foster kittens in the house. Learning from experience, if we could go back in time we would have taken all 3 in to be checked. We assumed it was territorial marking & we were wrong! Never assume, always get them checked. We were fortunate that we found her when we did & her vet saved her life after 4 days in the hospital. 🙏
This mentality was helpful with Halo just recently who had a watery eye that she was squinting. We didn't waste time even though we could've assumed it was just an allergy or something that got in her eye. We got her to the vet the same day. It turned out to be glaucoma & was causing her excruciating pain though she was hiding it well.

Happy 1 yr Adoptiversary Roo!
Exactly one year ago today, after a short period of fostering, we signed the adoption papers making Roo a FURever part of our family. 😺
A little background on Roo:
He was not bred this way. He was rescued by someone who witnessed someone else throwing him away like trash into a lake in a plastic bag likely because he was not normal like the rest of the litter. Luckily this other person saw this happen & brought him to @florida_humane_society where they adopted him out as a kitten.
Three years later he was returned by those adopters in very bad shape, emaciated. He was missing patches of fur and we recently noticed (if you compare to recent pics) that his "pouch" has fur on it now. When we got him we didn't think there ever was fur there.
He sat at Florida Humane Society for 6 months until we went there met him, and fell in love with all of the reasons that one person literally threw him away (probably the deformed kitten of a litter) and another neglected him and ultimately returned him like a bad product. Where they saw deformities and some neurological challenges we saw uniqueness, a sweet personality that was dying to be loved, and a cat that deserved a chance. He was very skittish when we first got him (almost a year ago) but he looks so much different and has gone from a scared boy that would hide all day and jump & scatter every time you walked by him to a very affectionate trusting and friendly boy who jumps at every chance to occupy lap space. He is so content and happy and his purrs are a daily reminder of how one man's trash can be another's treasure.
He has radial hypoplasia which is why his front legs are bent, abnormally large rear legs to compensate so he can stand up steady, crossed eyes, big ears, a big crooked tail that was most likely broken after birth, and we LOVE all of those things about him!
We fell in love with all the reasons someone else thought he was trash and that he didn't deserve to live.

What has big ears, crossed eyes, and is cute all over??? ROO...that's who! :) Meet the newest member of our family. After Mojo's unexpected passing we visited Florida Humane Society﻿ to give them a donation. We were not planning to adopt another cat but you know how that goes...... While we were there we spotted Roo standing upright as you see him in the pic. With his special legs, crossed eyes, and his story we fell in love. After really giving it some thought (due to just losing Mojo) we brought him home a week after meeting him. That was exactly 4 weeks ago. Today we officially adopted him & made him a forever part of our family after 4 weeks of fostering/monitoring & getting him adjusted to make sure everyone (furkids) was going to get along. It's been a very humbling & rewarding experience watching him grow from being scared to come out from under a chair to a kitty that comes to you when you call him and LOVES to snuggle. Every day he lets his guard down and trusts us a little more. I would say now that he is pretty settled. Here's his story.
Roo's life started out being born with a genetic mutation called Radial Hypoplasia also known as "twisty cat" or "kangaroo cat syndrome" hence his name (which we will keep the same because he answers to it) although we've given his name double meaning as he wakes us up right at dawn daily like clockwork like a rooster. Who could forget Buddy if you've been following since 2014?? We were asked to help a few day old kitten who had been thrown out of a car window. We got him with his eyes closed, burnt paw pads from the hot South Florida pavement, and a little scrawny lacerated tail. Buddy lost his tail as a result but thrived each week and ended up a handsome, strapping 22 lb tall and muscular "bobtail" cat. He's far from obese, just a huge frame and tall. He has a wonderful home now not far from where he was rescued from the street and is all grown up. He lives with 2 little girls who dress him up, tuck him in a baby doll bed, and push him around in a pink stroller. He loves every minute of it even though he's so masculine.
Fostering him & nursing him back to health was a wonderful self rewarding family experience. Cases like this is why we dive in hands on when we can and why we donate to rescue when we can. My own kids even helped hand on and have been since...little rescuers in training!
There are so many animals that need our help so please open your home to foster if you can! Sometimes rescues who are full will take on more if they have foster homes available. It's usually an issue of space, not $. My friend Hannah @kittenxlady has made kitten rescue her whole life! Check her out if you ❤️ kitten pics and a great cause. Tell her Venus sent ya! 😽

TNR turn rescue story....trapped this poor boy for TNR but ended up treating this awful case of conjunctivitis thought to be from Feline Herpes. He was neutered the first day and his wounds were treated along with a cortisone shot and Antibiotic injection while under anesthesia. These pics were taken over a 4 day period. He has since gone to a rescue friend who is experienced with handling ferals (he is very feral) for further treatment (eye drops and more vet visits) to heal his face before returning him to his colony. TNR isn't all about trap, spay/neuter, & return. Sometimes you get a case like this where you get to make a much more positive difference in their life than just sterilizing. Can you imagine the pain this poor boy was in? If you have a little spare time on your hands & want a self rewarding experience in an area that so desperately needs help, contact a local no-kill rescue to ask about volunteering to TNR. Cat overpopulation is so out of control that your contribution could make a huge difference. Have a great day everyone! 😽 Will post an update on this baby when he's all healed up. Look at those gorgeous green eyes that were under all of that painful mess. A great big HUGE thank you to Nicole and Suzanne for stepping in to further treat him & to Sharon, the business owner where the cats have been coming for food, for caring enough to NOT call animal control & instead reaching out to local rescues for not just him but another stray that needed TNR also which has been done. 💚💚

*This post is intended to share information based on my own experience, & documented cases, not to pass judgment or shame people. Everyone's situations and outcomes are different. Some of you w/ de-clawed cats may have had no post surgery issues but many have which is why it's banned in many countries and in some states in this country. It's also not to insinuate that all declawed cats will have issues...we don't want to deter anyone from adopting a declawed cat.
It's been said that declawed cats become biters. Well, 11 yrs ago, before we became educated on what declawing really is, we had Ginger's front claws removed as the vet recommended as a combo while she was being spayed. This was a very common recommendation & procedure coupled with spaying/neutering and in many veterinarians in the United States, still is. 😿👎 Again, this was before our involvement in rescue and before so much light has been shed on the truth. Hindsight is 20/20 and that said, we were wrong and learned from our mistake. Ginger IS a biter and we often wonder what other long term consequential side effects she might have suffered because of our ignorance. 😿
She was the last cat we ever had that procedure done on because we along with providing many scratch posts, we regularly trim the claws on the paws in this house with little to no resistance from the kitties attached to those paws.🐾

UODATE: Halo was seen by the ophthalmologist and the pressure in her eye was 44. Thankfully the other eye was 14 which is normal. The eye was unresponsive during a test and was confirmed to have no vision. Given the circumstances, the treatment plan recommended is removal of the eye. This is a very common scenario especially in certain breeds as I mentioned before. Even if she had vision it could be treated for a period of time but eventually would've had to be removed. There is no cure for Glaucoma, just management to control pressure. I also want to reiterate how quickly this can go from no symptoms at all to this severe. I like to share my experiences to hopefully help someone else. At the very first sign of eye trouble get to a vet!
We're sad that she's going to lose her eye and have to have surgery at all but relieved that she will no longer be in pain and will bounce back as we know how resilient our fur babies are. They said eye pain is one of the most painful things for dogs. Prayers as she undergoes the surgery. 🙏🙏
Thanks for all the well wishes and thoughtful comments. 😽😽
😿 Need Purrrayers for Halo. Her eye wasn't improving much & this morning she was not herself and very vocal about it so went to another vet to get a 2nd opinion. She has glaucoma. 😿

As a PSA, I learned today how quickly something like this can sneak up out of nowhere so I'd like to share this with you for awareness. Please educate yourself about glaucoma if you have a dog and see which breeds are more prone. Shiba Inus happen to be one of them. It's not curable but if you catch it early you can save your fur baby a lot of pain.
Please say a little prayer for her as we don't know what the recommended treatment/course of action will be. We will choose the least bothersome treatment so she can feel better as soon as possible. We are also praying that the pressure isn't high on the other eye. 🙏🙏🙏

🐕🐕 Halo update: Halo, who lost both eyes to glaucoma (one in Sept '16 & one June '17) is doing fantastic!
She's mastered the back steps and front steps to go for walks, ventures a little further each week now getting enough confidence to go past our property, and for the first time since losing her second eye, went up the stairs to the 2nd story yesterday where she slept every night til the 2nd enucleation.
She loves being out back (no fence yet so she's on a lead) learning her way and laying in the grass. She's much more confident and adventurous outdoors because she knows there are less things she can bump into. When she goes down our walkway you wouldn't even know she's blind without looking at her.
If you aren't familiar with glaucoma please learn about it. Halo is a Shiba Inu. 🐕
They are not formally on the list of breeds known to be predisposed to glaucoma but the amount of cases of Shibas with glaucoma I know about say otherwise. Even if your dog isn't "on the list" you should familiarize yourself with this condition. Symptoms often present only when it's too late and people often mistake the symptoms as seasonal allergies.
If you are dealing with or have dealt with glaucoma in your pet please share your story here so we can spread awareness and hopefully save others from being caught off guard by sharing our experiences. Thanks for the continued well wishes! 😽😽
